Summaries

five sample summaries

[1] The speaker in this TED talk emphasizes the crucial importance of reading fiction in our modern, complex world. He notes that the current era is marked by constant exposure to news and information , leading to a state of narcissism and intense individualism. We are desperately searching for answers and often turn to non- fiction books for productivity and life hacks. However, the speaker argues that given the increasing complexity of our world, it is vital to get out of our own eco chambers. Fiction, though at a slow pace, stimulates imagination and allows us to pay attention to language and metaphor. Ultimately, fiction serves as a life hack and an antidote to self-absorption, helping us to realize that the stranger is not so strange. It enables us to disconnect from ourselves and tap into an emotional and prosthetic side that we often neglect, enriching and changing us from the inside out.                                                                                                                         
[2] Did you read fiction books this year? Actually, nonfiction books have been on the rise in the past decade now.Fiction can offer something new, more knowledge on a certain subject, a life hack.He usually reads nonfiction books because that at least offers him something straightforward. Literary fiction can usher us into other worlds, and it can make a step into other realities. For example, Barack Obama learned from novels. It has to do with empathy, being comfortable with the notion that the world is complicated and full of grays, but there to be found.Empathy is the friendly enemy to our feeling of self-importance. Storytelling can help us to not only understand but feel the complexity, the emotions and the situations of distant others. It can be a vital antidote to the stress of all the noise around us like meditation. If you want them to be more intelligent, read them more fairytales                                                                                                                              
[3] This video explains why reading fiction is important for understanding others. Every day we see endless news, but it is often impersonal and does not help us feel what others feel. Many people read nonfiction because it gives clear information. But fiction can teach us empathy. Former President Obama said that he learned important lessons from novels. Fiction helps us imagine other peoples feelings and understand that the world is complicated. When we read a story, we follow the characters and think about how we would feel in their situation. This is called narrative immersion. It helps us focus and think deeply. Additionally, the speaker says that fiction is good for children because if you want your children to be intelligent, read them fairy tales, and if you want them to be very intelligent, read more fairy titles. Stories help children develop imagination and creativity. In a world full of social media and self focus, fiction helps us connect with others, understand the stranger,and grow from the inside.
[4] A lot of news is spreading these days, for example, forest fires, refugees and conflicts. Hearing this news, people may feel sadness or melancholy, worries. We need a wide outlook or proper knowledge to deal with this news. The speaker thinks reading nonfiction novels is good under the situation. Nonfiction focuses on one subject and tells the reader a true knowledge. Likewise, reading fiction novels have important functions. The speaker introduced statements of Barack Obama to show the benefits of fiction. Obama read fiction to understand others who have different positions. The speaker said it is empathy. Empathy is to consider complex situations and other feelings. When readers read fiction novels, they embrace deep feelings for the story because fiction triggers imagination about the story. The imagination is important for not only adults but also developing children. Reading fiction, children can be more creative.

Opinions

five sample opinions

[1] I have had a rich imagination since I was a child, and I am always imagining something in my head. This imagination has always helped me and given me something to pass the time. I had always thought that this imagination was an innate trait, but after listening to the speakers today, I began to think again and wonder if it might have been acquired from literature. The reason I came up with things that would never happen in real life was because I learned them in books. In addition, books have given us not only imagination but also vocabulary and rich sensibilities. I've heard that reading books makes you smarter, and after hearing his story, I'm convinced that this is true.
[2]                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                           
[3]                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                           
[4] I think that in this digital age, we spend too much time on fast, superficial reading like headlines and emails. The speaker correctly argues that we should consider what we are truly reading. The act of engaging with literary fiction offers a deep value far beyond simple knowledge. Reading novels requires "thought in action" and creates a state of "narrative immersion," shutting out the noise of the outside world. This is the joy of a single-tasking mind. In a world full of distractions, I believe this slow, focused act of exploring a story is the most valuable exercise we can do to regain our attention span and capacity for deeper reflection.                              
[5]
